        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Baseband Configuration:
This L.O. setting is designed to cover the CO isotopologues C18O and 13CO.  The weaker
isotopologue, C18O, sets our sensitivity limit for this science goal, however we also
request a baseband on 13CO, which is most likely optically thick at the stellar position, 
but may become optically thin in the outer radii of the disk where the sensitivity to
C18O drops, providing a secondary mass normalizer.  Optically thick 13CO (3-2) can also
help constrain the gas temperature, especially when used in tandem with the observations
of 12CO (2-1) and 13CO (2-1) reported in Panic et al. 2009.  Therefore these lines will
help better constrain the physical disk structure in the warm upper layers.  

We have added a baseband on HC18O+ (4-3), which, if thin will likely not be detected.  
The detection of the line means one of two things, A) our peak flux estimate of H13CO+  
was too conservative (i.e. HCO+ is more optically thick and H13CO+ is brighter -- see 
H13CO+ L.O setting), which we will readily determine from the line ratios measured by 
ALMA, or B) the H13CO+ line is thick and the HC18O+ line can be used to help measure deep 
ionization.  

Sensitivity Request:
We have estimated the 13CO (3-2) and C18O (3-2) peak line fluxes from 13CO (2-1) (Panic
et al. 2009), which was measured to have 0.8 Jy in a 1.8x1.2'' beam.  To estimate the 
13CO (2-1) in a smaller beam to predict 13CO (3-2), we use the fact that surface density 
is typically proportional to 1/R, and the emitting area goes as R^2, thus to first order 
the 13CO flux should be centrally peaked, with a flux contained in a beam of size (theta) 
increasing linearly with theta. For 13CO (2-1) in a 0.4'' beam we expect the flux to be
F(13CO) = 0.21 Jy.  From RADEX models at T=25 K, the 13CO (3-2) is typically brighter than 
the (2-1) by a factor of 3x.  Therefore we predict the 13CO (3-2) to be 0.64 Jy. 
If the 13CO is thin, we then expect C18O (3-2) to be a factor of 500/66 less bright,
or F(C18O) = 84 mJy.  This sets our sensitivity estimate of 12 mJy, such that we obtain
12 sigma on the line. 

Continuum:
The dust continuum is estimated from Pinte et al. 2008's observation of 1.3mm. The 1.3mm 
flux in a 1.84x1.25'' beam is 59 mJy.  Pinte provides a mm-spectral index of alpha=2.8\pm0.25.
From this we extrapolate the flux at 342.55 GHz to be 180 mJy, and correcting for a 0.4''
beam we expect 12.5 mJy on the continuum peak. 

We further note that in all L.O. configurations we have reduced the bandwidth to have a 
small data rate (&lt;6 MB/s), and in all we have included a continuum measurement to help 
with the data calibration. In all cases (L.O. settings) the continuum may be brighter 
if it is more centrally peaked within the larger beam.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
