        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Baseband Configuration:
This L.O. setting is driven by the need to detect N2H+.  While we have set the spectral 
resolution to be 0.4-0.6 km/s for the other settings (measured line width is ~4 km/s), 
the N2H+ (3-2) line is weaker and so to achieve sensitivity in substantially less time
we have relaxed our velocity resolution to 1 km/s, which we further note was what was
used for the SMA observations of the same line.

The N2H+ (3-2) peaks at ~0.4 Jy (Oberg et al. 2011) in an elongated beam of 5.3x2.5. 
Assuming the emission is more centrally peaked instead at the snow line, then we 
can compute the peak flux at the edge of the ring by instead comparing the ratio of the 
area of an N2H+ emitting ring to a narrow ring centered on the inner edge, which is
18 mJy.  Therefore we have requested high sensitivity observations to get a minimum
of 6 sigma on the line.

The DCO+ is observed by Oberg et al. 2011 to be weaker than N2H+ as integrated over the 
disk, however if it is centrally concentrated (expected if being produced by the "warm" 
deuterium pathways through CH2D+) then it may be accessible.  A measurement of DCO+
scientifically provides additional information on how the ionization state of the disk 
is feeding into the warm carbon-fueled deuterium chemistry, a potential source
of high D/H ratios in organic meteoritic material.  

Continuum:
We perform the same calculation as for the continuum point on the CO L.O. setting, 
instead at 1mm.  The computed flux is 113 mJy in the original continuum beam or 10 mJy 
in the corrected beam. </prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
