        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Baseband configuration.  
This L.O. setting targets two lines, H13CO+, HC18O+ (along with a continuum point for 
calibration purposes).  The sensitivity estimates therefore are pinned to the optically
thick main isotopologue HCO+.  Fortunately, we can calibrate the thickness of HCO+ using
a T Tauri disk with a similar X-ray luminosity, TW Hya (logLx=30.4).  Due to HCO+'s 
opacity, its emission is most sensitive to the temperature of the X-ray irradiated layers,
which drives the need to match X-ray luminosities in calibrating its thickness. To do
this we use observations of TW Hya's HCO+ (4-3) from the ALMA SV data and H13CO+ (4-3)
from Qi et al. 2004.  The measured fluxes are 7.46 Jy (beam of 1.7x1.6'') and 0.7 Jy 
(1.8x4.1'') respectively.   Correcting the H13CO+ for the smaller beam, the ratio of 
HCO+ (4-3)/H13CO+ (4-3)  = 28.7, i.e. the line is somewhat thick (tau ~ 2.3)

Returning to IM Lup, the HCO+ (3-2) was measured to be 6 Jy (5.3x2.5'') (Oberg et al. 2011).
In a 0.45'' beam this is 0.7 Jy, which is consistent with our 0.6'' resolution observations
of TW Hya on the same line at the same scale (both disks have similar absolute HCO+ (3-2)).

From the HCO+/H13CO+ ratio determined from TW Hya, we expect the H13CO+ 3-2 to be ~29x 
weaker than the main isotopologue, or 24 mJy, which is what sets our requested sensitivity
of 3 mJy.  Given that HC18O+ should be a factor of 500/66x weaker, or ~3 mJy.  Similar to
the discussion in the CO setting, we basically use HC18O+ to determine the opacity 
of H13CO+, and it has utility if it is detected (H13CO+ is thick, can then use HC18O+) or
if it's not detected H13CO+ is good to go.  The H13CO+ should be somewhat thick at the 
stellar position so we may in fact see HC18O+ there regardless. 

Continuum:
Same analysis as the other settings.  We expect the continuum flux at 243.1 GHz in a 
0.45'' beam to be 6 mJy. </prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
